I'd like to see something that makes more use of the population of such a city, and the internal politics. Most of Roman history comes down to the relationships between the people doing the politics, the cause and effect of rules, and of course how it affected the flow of history. The Marian Reforms are a good example, given how they were caused by Rome's expansion. Another thing that weird me out about a lot of citybuilders is how cities are often static, and the player decides where to put a lot of things. But especially a city like Rome grew organically. Apparently the ancestral home of Julius Caesar was in a part of town with a shitty reputation, but I assure you it certainly didn't start out that way. An anecdote of the time also states that a hardliner Roman senator personally put the axe to a temple of Isis, as it was a filthy imported religion, not only as a show but because everyone else felt kind of iffy about angering a god. That's the sort of shit I want to see in a game, rather than feeling forced to build a temple from the city budget to make numbers go up, and then doing the same for a textile shop for the plebs. Which will then stay in business for the next 200 years.

So more a city cultivator than a city builder. Except one where I can sic angry mobs on annoying senators.

I don't think that kind of complexity was doable at the time of the early SimCity/Civ/Caesar games.
But it is an interesting blend. Do you spend your money/resources on what you want, or sell it to the citizenry to go in a different direction? Of course, they still have to ask your permission, slums excepted. Upgrades come when you grant favor, which is an entirely separate resource line and much more rare.
The more organic it is, the harder it is for you to control and the more internal revolts. The less organic it is, the less you can tolerate outside attacks and political coups.

Procedural generation used to be a big thing back in the 90s games, and it could give you either a fast-paced interactive game or a very slow-paced idle game.
Transforming barbarians into anthro factions would just be what sets it higher. Who do you allow in and how do their factions aid your city?
